Uhhhh I'm not particularly versed in anecdotes/proverbs; sorry
I could try to look some up if that would help

I mean the idiom/phrase for "removing yourself from something bad" or "going clean" is 足を洗う (ashi wo arau; literally "to wash your feet"). It's tied into the Shinto religion, and the common theory is that it specifically came from monks washing their feet after walking barefoot outside, which was believed to also have the effect of washing away worldly desires.

As for tattoos that's a bit of a tougher one since people in Japan (generally) only get tattoos while IN the Yakuza; not after they've already gotten out. As such expect a lot of generic dragons, demons, and basic-bitch kanji like 力 (power/strength) 悪 (evil) and shit like that.
